Knowing how Nature intends for us to breathe and make sound will make a huge impact on your control and confidence.

4. Proper breathing technique –
learn how to use Belly Breathing and “sing from the diaphragm”. It is difficult to create a flow when you sing or speak if we can see your shoulders lifting up and down and hear you sucking in air.
Your voice goes where your eyes go—don’t close your eyes a lot or look over people’s heads. Look us in the eye for a few seconds and you’ll win our hearts.

3. Sing To Your Audience, Not at Them –
split the audience into quadrants and sing to each quadrant for a few seconds. Even if you’re not making eye contact with every single person it will look and feel as if you’re singing to each audience member.

2. Use Dynamics 
nothing is boring like a song that sounds the same from beginning to end. You have to change up the volume, the intensity, the tone and all other vocal elements to keep people engaged. Accent key words in each line by make them different—louder/softer, brighter..

'Make this a Routine When Performing Live On Stage’

1. Know Your Song –
have the words memorized and have 2 or 3 emotions that you want to evoke when you sing. Trying to sing with emotion is hard when you don’t know which emotion(s) to use.

4. Self Awareness
When you are consistently aware of your singing voice, you will be well attuned to knowing if you are able to hit the right notes, produce the right pitches and have a better idea as to how you sound.

3. Dynamics and Style
Singing every note and pitch very loud without thinking about dynamics is a sign of unprofessionalism. A good singer doesn’t smash into a song just like that, but finds a reasonable volume and style that works for both the song and the vocal cords.

Once you get control over your voice, you begin to win the battle of developing your best voice.

2. Stay Original

Know your vocal range and stay within, as well listen to yourself. Use your ears along with your voice when singing.
